{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"medium","title":"Beacon proxies can be left uninitialized and then fully hijacked","locations":["onchain_auto/0x5d94309e5a0090b165fa4181519701637b6daeba/packages/contracts-core/contracts/upgrade/UpgradeBeaconProxy.sol:40","onchain_auto/0x5d94309e5a0090b165fa4181519701637b6daeba/packages/contracts-core/contracts/upgrade/UpgradeBeaconProxy.sol:54","onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/Replica.sol:103","onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/NomadBase.sol:82"],"claim":"`UpgradeBeaconProxy` explicitly allows deployment with empty initialization calldata. `Replica.initialize` is a public `initializer` that sets ownership, updater, remote domain, committed root, and optimistic timeout via `__NomadBase_initialize`. If a beacon proxy is ever deployed without constructor-time init data, the first external caller can initialize it through the proxy and seize full control of the replica.","impact":"A forgotten or failed initialization becomes a full bridge takeover. The attacker can become owner, choose an attacker-controlled updater and trusted root, then prove and process forged messages, enabling arbitrary cross-chain message execution and asset theft.","paths":["Deploy `UpgradeBeaconProxy` with `_initializationCalldata.length == 0`.","Before the intended operator initializes it, an attacker calls `Replica.initialize(...)` through the proxy.","The initializer makes the attacker the owner and sets attacker-chosen updater/root parameters.","The attacker proves messages against the attacker-chosen committed root and processes arbitrary payloads on the destination chain."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Updater signatures are replayable across deployments that reuse the same domain and updater key","locations":["onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/NomadBase.sol:101","onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/NomadBase.sol:126","onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/Replica.sol:313"],"claim":"The updater signature digest is only `keccak256(homeDomainHash(), oldRoot, newRoot)`, and `homeDomainHash()` only binds the 32-bit remote domain plus the string `NOMAD`. It does not bind the signature to a specific Home contract, Replica contract, chain id, or deployment instance.","impact":"If two deployments ever reuse the same remote domain and updater key, a valid update signed for one deployment is also valid on the other. That can import foreign roots into the wrong replica and authorize processing of messages that never belonged to that bridge, leading to cross-environment fund theft or arbitrary message execution.","paths":["A second deployment is configured with the same `remoteDomain` and `updater` as an existing deployment.","The updater signs `(oldRoot, newRoot)` for deployment A.","Anyone relays the same signature to deployment B while B has the same current `committedRoot`.","Deployment B accepts deployment A's root and starts proving/processing messages from the wrong environment."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Replica silently truncates 32-byte recipients to 20 bytes and dispatches to non-contract addresses","locations":["onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/libs/Message.sol:106","onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/libs/TypeCasts.sol:44","onchain_auto/0x7f221a1850c12b57fed1f0831dd25399a13b68c2/packages/contracts-core/contracts/Replica.sol:199"],"claim":"The message format commits to a full 32-byte recipient, but execution converts it with `address(uint160(uint256(_buf)))`, silently discarding the upper 12 bytes. `process()` then calls `handle` on the truncated address without verifying that code exists there or that the target actually implements the expected interface.","impact":"Malformed or non-canonical recipient encodings can be misdelivered or black-holed on the destination chain. A message can be marked processed even when it was routed to an EOA or unintended contract, causing irreversible loss of the bridged action and potential permanent lockup of user funds.","paths":["A message is committed with a 32-byte recipient whose upper 12 bytes are non-zero or whose lower 20 bytes resolve to an EOA/wrong contract.","`recipientAddress()` truncates the recipient to the low 20 bytes.","`process()` dispatches to that truncated address without any code/interface check.","The message is irrevocably marked processed even though the intended recipient logic never ran."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"The documented `Failed` state does not actually stop updates or message execution","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"The `state` variable is indeed unused, but this codebase exposes no reachable path that ever sets `state = Failed`; in the current implementation it is dead code/comment drift rather than an exploitable protocol flaw."},{"title":"Updater rotation can permanently orphan already-signed but unrelayed roots","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Changing `updater` invalidates old signatures, but the new updater can re-sign the same root transition or any later append-only root, so the code does not itself permanently strand messages."},{"title":"Missing Origin Domain Verification Allows Arbitrary Cross-Domain Message Injection","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The message `origin` field is authenticated by Merkle inclusion in an updater-signed root for the followed Home; lack of a separate `origin == remoteDomain` check is not a standalone forgery vector."},{"title":"prove() Allows Re-proving Messages Under New Roots Without Validation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Re-proving an unprocessed message under another acceptable root is intentional append-only behavior and does not bypass the processed check or create capabilities beyond whatever roots are already trusted."},{"title":"Governance Can Set Arbitrary Roots Bypassing Security Controls","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`setConfirmation` is an explicit owner-only emergency override; a malicious or compromised governance owner is a trust assumption, not a distinct implementation bug."},{"title":"Single Updater Key Creates Centralized Single Point of Failure","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a protocol trust-model observation rather than a code vulnerability; the contracts are explicitly designed around a trusted updater role."},{"title":"Optimistic Timeout Can Be Set To Zero During Initialization","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The lack of a minimum on first initialization is an explicit deployment/configuration choice for testing/bootstrap scenarios and requires trusted deployment misconfiguration, not a permissionless exploit."},{"title":"No Protection Against Proof Reuse After Message Processing","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Processed messages cannot be reproven because `prove()` rejects `LEGACY_STATUS_PROCESSED`; reproving before processing is the same intended behavior already covered by the other re-proving candidate and is not independently exploitable."},{"title":"process() Does Not Check Return Value of handle() External Call","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`IMessageRecipient.handle` has no return value; if the external call reverts, the whole transaction reverts and the processed status/event are rolled back, so there is no false-success path from an ignored return value."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Check for Updater","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Setting `updater` to `address(0)` is recoverable by the owner via a later `setUpdater` call, so it does not permanently brick the bridge and is not a protocol-level vulnerability."}]}
